findGlobalFunction

public GlobalFunction findGlobalFunction(java.lang.String name,
                                         java.lang.String... paramTypes)
Retrieves the global function with the given name. If there are multiple global functions with the given name, paramTypes must be used to specify the right global function to be returned. If no paramTypes is specified, a global function is returned if there is only one global function with the given name, or if there is one global function with the name that does not contain any parameter. If no global function is found for the given name, null is returned.

Parameters:
name - name of the global function to be returned
Returns:
global function

commit

public void commit()
Call commit() to save the changes of the current pending logical operation you are performing. An example of a logical operation includes creating a custom object, adding a custom field, adding a trigger, adding a validation rule, adding a object function, or performing the edit variants of these. When used in this way, all of the metadata changes saved for a single logical operation are atomic: that is, either all will succeed or all will fail. Therefore, at this time, the recommended usage of this API is to call commit() once per each logical transaction. If you ignore this recommendation and perform multiple logical operations before calling commit(), then this method attempts to individually save each logical operation performed since the last commit in a separate transaction. If any of the transactions performed results in an error, then the set of logical changes that you attempt to commit together will not represent an atomic operation. Some may be saved, while others are not.

Throws:

rollback
